You need to implement `func collectionView(_ collectionView: UICollectionView, didSelectItemAt indexPath: IndexPath)`. See [Apple docs][1]

Inside it, you can call your segue, which navigates to next controller, e.g.:

    func collectionView(_ collectionView: UICollectionView, didSelectItemAt indexPath: IndexPath) {
        // Get selected row, you can then do something for each row
        let selectedRow = indexPath.row // can also get indexPath.section or .item
        self.performSegue(withIdentifier: &quot;your identifier&quot;, sender: self)
    }

If you want to pass some data from first controller to the next, you could pass a data in `override func prepareForSegue(segue: UIStoryBoardSegue, sender: AnyObject?)`:

    override func prepareForSegue(segue: UIStoryboardSegue, sender: AnyObject?) {
        if segue.identifier == &quot;your identifier&quot; {
            var dest = segue.destinationViewController as! YourViewControllerType
            dest.anotherArray = [&quot;whatever&quot;, &quot;you&quot;, &quot;want&quot;]
    }

Of course it&#39;s assumed that `YourViewControllerType` will have a member `var anotherArray: [String]?` (type and name can be changed of course).

A better way is to define a proper model class which will hold the data for destination controller.

  [1]: https://developer.apple.com/documentation/uikit/uicollectionviewdelegate/1618032-collectionview

